"id":"33219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44984"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his mother with a one-week history of a papular, erythematous eruption affecting most of his body. He has been scratching persistently and is now struggling to sleep and concentrate at school, though he otherwise feels well. He has a history of asthma and had eczema as a baby. He does not take any regular medications. The family lives in a house with eight occupants spanning three generations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple excoriated erythematous papules, predominantly on the hands and feet. Dermoscopy of the web spaces reveals a \u0027delta sign\u0027 and \u0027jet with contrail pattern\u0027. Several areas of skin show evidence of secondary infection. The diagnosis is explained to the boy and his mother, and management is discussed. The family denies that other household members are affected, but his mother is concerned about her elderly parent, who is immunosuppressed and lives with them. She is worried about the risk of others developing this problem.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant risk factor for scabies transmission in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Poor hygiene","Housing situation","Immunodeficiency","Prior history of eczema","Attending school"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is scabies, based on the history of intense pruritus, excoriated papules in acral sites, and characteristic dermoscopic findings. \u003Cstrong\u003EHousing situation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant risk factor in this scenario. Overcrowded living conditions facilitate close and prolonged skin-to-skin contact, which is the primary mode of scabies transmission. Children and people living in multi-generational or institutional settings are at increased risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttending school\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with exposure, but transmission is less likely in brief contacts typical of school settings compared to the prolonged contact in households. The risk of spread is highest among people sharing living spaces, especially when treatment of all contacts is not ensured.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor hygiene\u003C/strong\u003E is a common misconception but is not a risk factor for scabies. The mite is transmitted by direct contact, not by lack of cleanliness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunodeficiency\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of developing crusted (Norwegian) scabies, a severe form, but is not a primary risk factor for classical scabies transmission. In this case, the concern for the immunosuppressed household member is valid for severe disease, but not for initial acquisition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrior history of eczema\u003C/strong\u003E may complicate the clinical picture or be a differential diagnosis, but it does not increase the risk of acquiring scabies. Eczema may also develop as a reaction to scabies infestation, but is not a predisposing factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Overcrowded housing is the most significant risk factor for scabies transmission, especially in children.","Scabies is primarily spread by prolonged skin-to-skin contact, with household contacts at highest risk.","Immunodeficiency increases risk for crusted scabies, but not for classical scabies."],"references":["Engelman D, Yoshizumi J, Hay RJ, Osti M, Micali G, et al. The 2020 International Alliance for the Control of Scabies Consensus Criteria for the Diagnosis of Scabies. Br J Dermatol. 2020;183(5):808-820. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7687112/","Thomas C, Coates SJ, Engelman D, Chosidow O, Chang AY. Ectoparasites: Scabies. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2020;82(3):533-548. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31310840/","Hardy M, Engelman D, Steer A. Scabies: A clinical update. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(5):264-268. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/may/scabies-a-clinical-update"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85166"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2630"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85166"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-14T14:06:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-14T14:08:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2630"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attribute